Here's a simple implementation of a function that converts Markdown to HTML using the Pugcpp library. This library can be installed via apt-get in Ubuntu-based systems. 

Please note that this is a basic implementation and does not cover all edge cases and variations of Markdown. 

Here's the code:

```cpp
#include <pugcpp/v2/markdown.hpp>
#include <string>

std::string ConvertMarkdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugcpp::Markdown md;
    return md.html(markdown);
}
```

You can use it like this:

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello, _world!_";
    std::string html = ConvertMarkdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this case, the output would be:

```
<p>Hello, <em>world!</em></p>
```

This code only converts a few basic Markdown syntax to HTML. For more advanced Markdown rendering, you may need a more complex solution. Some options include using a library like doxys, or writing your own Markdown parser. 

Here's a more complex example with a basic implementation of a Markdown parser:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string ConvertMarkdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Handle bold text
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("([*]{1})([^*]+)([*]{1})", std::regex::format_first_only, "<b>$2</b>"));

    // Handle italic text
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("(_)([^_]+)(_)"), std::regex::format_first_only, "<i>$2</i>");

    // Handle links
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("[(](.*?)[)]\\((.*?)\\)", std::regex::format_first_only, "<a href=\"$2\" target=\"_blank\">$1</a>")));

    // Handle headers
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("^(#{1,6}) (.*)$", std::regex::format_first_only, "<h$1>$2</h$1>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello, _world!_ [Visit Google](http://www.google.com) # This is a header";
    std::string html = ConvertMarkdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we use the `<regex>` header and the `std::regex_replace` function to replace certain patterns in the Markdown with their corresponding HTML equivalent. You can add more patterns to this function as needed to support more complex Markdown features. 

This is a very basic Markdown parser and there are many edge cases it won't handle correctly. For example, it doesn't handle nested links or bold text, or blockquotes. These features would require implementing additional logic to properly parse and render the Markdown syntax.

To implement the Snake game in C with animation using images, you'll need to use a library that can handle graphics and animation. One popular choice is SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer). Here's a basic example of how you can implement it. Please note that this is a simplified version and doesn't include all the features of the classic Snake game.

**Prerequisites:**

1. Install SDL library on your system.
2. Install SDL Development Library (SDL-devel) on your system.
3. Install a C compiler (e.g., GCC) if you haven't already.

**Code:**

```c
#include <SDL.h>
#include <SDL_image.h>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <time.h>

// Window dimensions
const int WIDTH = 640;
const int HEIGHT = 480;

// Snake game constants
const int SNAKE_SPEED = 5;
const int SNAKE_SIZE = 20;

// Define directions
enum Direction { UP, DOWN, LEFT, RIGHT };

// Structure to represent a snake body part
struct SnakePart {
    int x;
    int y;
};

// Structure to represent the snake
struct Snake {
    std::vector<SnakePart> body;
    Direction direction;
};

// Game variables
Snake snake;
SDL_Surface* screen;
SDL_Surface* snakePartImage;
SDL_Surface* foodImage;
SDL_Rect snakeRect;
SDL_Rect foodRect;
int score = 0;
bool gameOver = false;
bool running = true;

// Function to load images
void loadImages() {
    // Load snake part image
    snakePartImage = IMG_Load("snake_part.png");
    if (!snakePartImage) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to load snake part image!" << std::endl;
        exit(1);
    }

    // Load food image
    foodImage = IMG_Load("food.png");
    if (!foodImage) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to load food image!" << std::endl;
        exit(1);
    }
}

// Function to draw everything
void draw() {
    // Fill screen with black color
    SDL_FillRect(screen, &screen->clip_rect, SDL_MapRGB(screen->format, 0, 0, 0));

    // Draw snake
    for (int i = 0; i < snake.body.size(); i++) {
        SDL_Rect rect = { snake.body[i].x * SNAKE_SIZE, snake.body[i].y * SNAKE_SIZE, SNAKE_SIZE, SNAKE_SIZE };
        SDL_BlitSurface(snakePartImage, NULL, screen, &rect);
    }

    // Draw food
    SDL_Rect rect = { foodRect.x, foodRect.y, foodRect.w, foodRect.h };
    SDL_BlitSurface(foodImage, NULL, screen, &rect);

    // Update screen
    SDL_UpdateRects(screen, 1, &screen->clip_rect);
}

// Function to handle user input
void handleInput() {
    SDL_Event event;
    while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
        if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
            running = false;
        } else if (event.type == SDL_KEYDOWN) {
            switch (event.key.keysym.sym) {
                case SDLK_UP:
                    if (snake.direction != DOWN) {
                        snake.direction = UP;
                    }
                    break;
                case SDLK_DOWN:
                    if (snake.direction != UP) {
                        snake.direction = DOWN;
                    }
                    break;
                case SDLK_LEFT:
                    if (snake.direction != RIGHT) {
                        snake.direction = LEFT;
                    }
                    break;
                case SDLK_RIGHT:
                    if (snake.direction != LEFT) {
                        snake.direction = RIGHT;
                    }
                    break;
            }
        }
    }
}

// Main game loop
int main() {
    // Initialize SDL
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO | SDL_INIT_AUDIO);
    screen = SDL_SetVideoMode(WIDTH, HEIGHT, 32, SDL_SWSURFACE);
    loadImages();

    // Set initial snake position
    snake.body.push_back({ WIDTH / 2, HEIGHT / 2 });
    snake.direction = RIGHT;

    // Main game loop
    while (running) {
        handleInput();

        // Move snake
        snake.body.push_back({ snake.body.back().x + (snake.direction == RIGHT ? SNAKE_SIZE : snake.direction == LEFT ? -SNAKE_SIZE : snake.direction == UP ? 0 : SNAKE_SIZE), snake.body.back().y + (snake.direction == DOWN ? SNAKE_SIZE : snake.direction == UP ? -SNAKE_SIZE : 0) });

        // Check for collisions and scoring
        if (snake.body.back().x < 0 || snake.body.back().x >= WIDTH / SNAKE_SIZE || snake.body.back().y < 0 || snake.body.back().y >= HEIGHT / SNAKE_SIZE) {
            gameOver = true;
        } else {
            for (int i = 0; i < snake.body.size() - 1; i++) {
                if (snake.body.back().x == snake.body[i].x && snake.body.back().y == snake.body[i].y) {
                    gameOver = true;
                }
            }
        }

        if (snake.body.back().x == foodRect.x && snake.body.back().y == foodRect.y) {
            score++;
            snake.body.pop_back();
        } else {
            snake.body.erase(snake.body.begin());
        }

        // Place food randomly
        int x = rand() % (WIDTH / SNAKE_SIZE);
        int y = rand() % (HEIGHT / SNAKE_SIZE);
        foodRect = { x * SNAKE_SIZE, y * SNAKE_SIZE, SNAKE_SIZE, SNAKE_SIZE };

        // Draw everything
        SDL_Flip(screen);
        draw();

        // Delay to control the game speed
        SDL_Delay(1000 / SNAKE_SPEED);
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_Quit();
    IMG_FreeSurface(snakePartImage);
    IMG_FreeSurface(foodImage);
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. The code uses SDL2 for graphics and image handling.
2. The `loadImages()` function loads the snake part and food images.
3. The `draw()` function draws the snake, food, and updates the screen.
4. The `handleInput()` function handles user input (arrow keys) to control the snake's direction.
5. The main game loop moves the snake, checks for collisions, updates the score, and draws everything.
6. The game ends when the snake hits the edge or itself.

**Note:** This is a basic implementation, and you'll need to add more features (e.g., scorekeeping, level design, and smoother animation) to create a full-fledged game.

**Compiling and running:**

1. Compile the code using `gcc`:
```bash
gcc snake_game.c -o snake_game -lSDL2 -lSDL2_image
```
2. Run the game:
```bash
./snake_game
```

**Additional dependencies:**

* SDL2 development library (SDL2-devel)
* SDL2 image library (SDL2_image)
* `gcc` compiler

Make sure to install these dependencies and adjust the compilation command according to your system's requirements.

